snippet.textDisplay:
Some 20 years ago while sitting through a particularly boring CS class in school i came across the Feigenbaum constant in a book i was reading at the time. The almighty curriculum demanded we do what essentially amounted to a basic intro on how to use MS Office with a focus on Excel - no Visual Basic or any of that other fancy stuff, just the bare essentials no coding skills required. Surely useful skills to have but not quite what we expected either.
So when it came time to choose a end-of-year project a friend and i decided to stage a little nerd rebellion. Remembering aforementioned book we settled on a Excel sheet that would generate the logistic map, visualize it and compute the Feigenbaum constant from it. What we ended up with was a fully interactive beautiful little monstrosity that allowed us to explore its fractal nature much like what you can see in this video.
Technically fulfilling the only constraint for the project being that it be made with Excel we managed to score a full 15/15 points (the equivalent of an A+) - allegedly the first A+ this teacher had ever given. More importantly however it helped strengthen a friendship lasting to this very day.
So thank you Veritasium for bringing back this memory!
